# Style Guide — Developer Documentation

## Voice and tone

Write like you're explaining something to a smart colleague who's new to this specific thing. Not a beginner — a capable person who's missing context.

**Direct.** Say what you mean. Don't hedge unless the hedge is load-bearing.

| Instead of | Write |
|---|---|
| You may want to consider using... | Use... |
| It is possible to configure... | You can configure... |
| This function can be utilized to... | Use this function to... |

**Second person.** Address the reader as "you." Avoid "the user" (it creates distance) and "we" (it's ambiguous).

**Present tense.** Describe what the system does, not what it will do.

| Instead of | Write |
|---|---|
| The function will return an array. | The function returns an array. |
| Clicking Submit will save the form. | Clicking Submit saves the form. |

**Active voice.** Put the subject first and make it do something.

| Instead of | Write |
|---|---|
| The token is generated by the API. | The API generates a token. |
| An error will be thrown if... | The function throws an error if... |

---

## Terminology

**Be consistent.** Pick one term for one thing and use it throughout. Don't alternate between "token," "key," and "credential" to avoid repetition — repetition is fine, ambiguity is not.

**Define on first use.** When you introduce a term the reader may not know, define it in plain language at first mention. After that, use the term without re-explaining.

**Match the product.** Use the exact strings the UI or API uses. If the button says "Create project," the doc says "Create project" — not "create a new project" or "set up a project."

**Avoid jargon without context.** Abbreviations and internal terms are fine once defined. Never use an abbreviation before defining it.

---

## Grammar and mechanics

### Headings

- Use sentence case: "Getting started with the API" not "Getting Started With The API"
- Headings are labels, not teasers. Tell the reader what's in the section.
- Don't use a heading for a single paragraph. If the content can stand alone without a label, let it.

### Lists

Use a bulleted list when:
- The items have no required order
- There are 3 or more items that would make a sentence unwieldy

Use a numbered list when:
- Order matters (steps in a procedure)
- The reader needs to track their position

**Parallel structure.** All items in a list should start the same way — all verbs, all nouns, all sentences. Don't mix.

| Inconsistent | Parallel |
|---|---|
| Configure the endpoint / Setting up auth / You also need a token | Configure the endpoint / Set up authentication / Generate a token |

### Code

- Use inline code formatting for: file names, function names, parameter names, CLI commands, and any string the reader would type or copy.
- Use code blocks for: multi-line code, terminal output, and configuration files.
- Always specify the language on code blocks so syntax highlighting works.
- Include comments in code examples only when the code's purpose isn't obvious.

### Numbers

- Spell out numbers zero through nine. Use numerals for 10 and above.
- Exception: always use numerals in technical contexts (version numbers, measurements, code values).

### Capitalization

- Capitalize proper nouns: product names, feature names that are official.
- Don't capitalize common nouns to make them seem important: "the dashboard," not "the Dashboard."
- UI element names follow whatever the UI uses.

---

## Procedures (step-by-step instructions)

Each step should contain one action. If the reader has to do two things, that's two steps.

**Lead with the verb.** Steps start with what the reader does, not with context.

| Instead of | Write |
|---|---|
| After configuring your environment, you can run the build. | Run the build. |
| In order to authenticate, a token must be generated. | Generate an authentication token. |

**Confirm completion.** When the outcome of a step is visible, tell the reader what to look for.

> 3. Click **Deploy**.
>
>    The status indicator changes to "Deploying." When deployment is complete, the status changes to "Active."

---

## Accessibility

- **Alt text for images:** Describe what the image shows, not what it is. "A diagram showing the three-step OAuth flow" not "OAuth diagram."
- **Link text:** Use descriptive link text that makes sense out of context. "See the authentication guide" not "click here."
- **Heading hierarchy:** Don't skip heading levels. H3 follows H2, not H1.
- **Tables:** Include a header row. Don't use tables for layout — only for genuinely tabular data.
- **Code examples:** When a code example relies on a visual diagram, include a text description of the diagram.

---

## What to avoid

**Filler phrases** — cut these on sight:

- "Please note that..."
- "It's important to remember..."
- "In order to..."
- "As mentioned above..."
- "Feel free to..."

**Vague modifiers:**

- "simply," "just," "easily," "quickly" — if it's simple, the instructions will show it. If it's not simple, you're lying.

**Over-explanation of obvious things.** Trust that the reader is capable. If they need to click a button, say "click [Button name]" — not "locate the button labeled [Button name] and use your mouse to click on it."
